  "prompt": "What are your 10 favorite horror movies?",
  "response": "Here are ten highly regarded horror movies that many fans and critics alike consider to be among the best in the genre:\n\n1. **The Shining (1980)** - Directed by Stanley Kubrick, this psychological horror film based on Stephen King's novel is known for its chilling atmosphere and Jack Nicholson\u2019s iconic performance.\n\n2. **Hereditary (2018)** - A modern classic directed by Ari Aster, this film explores themes of grief and family trauma, delivering shocking moments and a haunting atmosphere.\n\n3. **Get Out (2017)** - Jordan Peele\u2019s masterful social thriller combines horror with sharp social commentary, making it a standout in contemporary horror cinema.\n\n4. **Rosemary's Baby (1968)** - Directed by Roman Polanski, this film addresses themes of paranoia and motherhood, creating an unsettling atmosphere throughout.\n\n5. **Psycho (1960)** - Alfred Hitchcock\u2019s seminal thriller is known for its groundbreaking narrative techniques and is often considered one of the greatest films in cinema history.\n\n6. **The Exorcist (1973)** - Widely regarded as one of the scariest films of all time, this movie about demonic possession has left a lasting impact on the horror genre.\n\n7. **A Nightmare on Elm Street (1984)** - Wes Craven\u2019s iconic slasher film introduced the memorable character Freddy Krueger and explored the concept of nightmares becoming reality.\n\n8. **The Babadook (2014)** - This psychological horror film by Jennifer Kent delves into grief and motherhood, creating an emotional and terrifying experience.\n\n9. **Suspiria (1977)** - Dario Argento's visually stunning film combines horror with surrealism, set against the backdrop of a dance academy with dark secrets.\n\n10. **It Follows (2014)** - A unique take on the horror genre, this film uses a metaphorical curse to explore themes of intimacy and anxiety, all while maintaining a tense atmosphere.\n\nThese films span various styles and eras, showcasing the diversity and depth of the horror genre.",
